Security Operations Fundamentals > [T4]: Security Standards: Compliance is Mandatory

Standards

A standard is a set of requirements, typically system or technology specific, that must be adhered to by everyone. Standards are mandatory to comply with.

An example of a security standard is The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, also known as PCI DSS. It's a mandatory standard to comply with for organizations handling credit card information, such as banks and payment gateways. The PCI DSS standard existed to assure the security of credit card holders' data and verify that financial entities apply best security practices to protect data.

Almost every sector has its security standard. HIPAA is a security standard for healthcare organizations handling patients' data. Hospitals must comply with HIPAA to ensure that patients' data are always protected.
 

Figure - zoom in

Another well-known security standard is the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Cybersecurity Framework. NIST is a non-regulatory government agency that develops technology, metrics, and standards to drive innovation and economic competitiveness at US-based organizations in the science and technology industry.

The core components of the NIST Cybersecurity framework are the following:

  1. Identify covers determining the assets you will protect.
  2. Protect covers how to protect your assets using suitable safeguards and security measures.
  3. Detect covers how to identify and detect cyber attacks against your organization.
  4. Respond: covers handling and responding to cyber-attacks.
  5. Recover: covers how to recover from a cyber attack and return to normal.
